\begin_layout Title
Reflection, Transmission and Absorption of Light across Conducting Surfaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Jo√£o Pedro dos Santos Pires
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
In these notes, I calculate the transmittance, reflectance and absorbance
 of a conducting surface between two dielectrics, as a function of the media's
 constitutive relations.
 We start by deriving expressions for the fields and energy flux of an electroma
gnetic wave moving across a three-dimensional linear dielectric medium.
 Then we move on to study the appropriate boundary conditions to be applied
 in the interface between two such media.
 We finish by applying these expressions to calculate the angle-resolved
 reflectance and transmittance of an interface were a two-dimensional conductor
 is placed.
 This problem had been considered before by Stauber et al
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "key-2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Then we introduce the transfer-matrix method allowing us to calculate the
 same quantities for stratified structures.
\begin_inset CommandInset toc
LatexCommand tableofcontents

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Energy Carried by an Electromagnetic Plane-Wave in a Dielectric
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Electromagnetic Plane-Waves in 3D
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We start by deriving an expression for the energy transported by an electromagne
tic plane wave, moving in an infinite homogeneous dielectric medium with
 a dielectric constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{m}$
\end_inset

 (we will take the medium to be non-magnetic, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{m}=\mu_{0}$
\end_inset

).
 The corresponding electric and magnetic fields of the (progressive) plane-waves
 can be written as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\overrightarrow{E}_{\overrightarrow{k}}\left(\overrightarrow{r},t\right) & =\overrightarrow{E}_{0,\overrightarrow{k}}e^{i\left(\overrightarrow{k}\cdot\overrightarrow{r}-\omega t\right)}\label{eq:ElectricFieldPlaneWave}\\
\overrightarrow{B}_{\overrightarrow{k}}\left(\overrightarrow{r},t\right) & =\overrightarrow{B}_{0,\overrightarrow{k}}e^{i\left(\overrightarrow{k}\cdot\overrightarrow{r}-\omega t\right)}.\label{eq:MagneticFieldPlaneWave}
\end{align}

\end_inset

These expressions are not independent, as they are connected by the electromagne
tic Maxwell's Equations, which read
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{cc}
\nabla\cdot\vect D\left(\overrightarrow{r},t\right)= & 0\\
\nabla\cdot\vect B\left(\overrightarrow{r},t\right)= & 0\\
\nabla\times\vect E\left(\overrightarrow{r},t\right)= & -\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\vect B\left(\overrightarrow{r},t\right)\\
\nabla\times\vect H\left(\overrightarrow{r},t\right)= & \frac{\partial}{\partial t}\vect D\left(\overrightarrow{r},t\right)
\end{array},\label{eq:Maxwell'sEquations}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

in the absence of free charges or currents.
 These must to be complemented by dielectric constitutive relations associated
 to the dielectric medium when they are propagating, i.e.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{cc}
\vect D\left(\overrightarrow{r},t\right)= & \varepsilon_{m}\vect E\left(\overrightarrow{r},t\right)\\
\vect H\left(\overrightarrow{r},t\right)= & \frac{1}{\mu_{0}}\vect B\left(\overrightarrow{r},t\right)
\end{array},\label{eq:ConstitutiveRelations}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where we assumed the propagation medium to be a linear one.
 If we plug Eqs.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ConstitutiveRelations"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 into Eqs.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Maxwell'sEquations"

\end_inset

, we get the following version of the Maxwell's Equations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{cc}
\nabla\cdot\vect E\left(\overrightarrow{r},t\right)= & 0\\
\nabla\cdot\vect B\left(\overrightarrow{r},t\right)= & 0\\
\nabla\times\vect E\left(\overrightarrow{r},t\right)= & -\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\vect B\left(\overrightarrow{r},t\right)\\
\nabla\times\vect B\left(\overrightarrow{r},t\right)= & \mu_{0}\varepsilon_{m}\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\vect E\left(\overrightarrow{r},t\right)
\end{array},\label{eq:Maxwell'sEquations-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and using the third of these equations, together with the expressions for
 the plane-wave fields, Eqs.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ElectricFieldPlaneWave"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:MagneticFieldPlaneWave"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we arrive at the following relation between the amplitudes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\vect k\cdot\vect E_{0,\vect k} & =0\label{eq:k.E}\\
\vect k\cdot\vect B_{0,\vect k}= & 0\label{eq:k.B}\\
\vect k\times\vect E_{0,\vect k}= & \omega\vect B_{0,\vect k}\label{eq:kcrossE}\\
\vect k\times\vect B_{0,\vect k}= & -\mu_{0}\varepsilon_{m}\omega\vect E_{0,\vect k}.\label{eq:kcrossB}
\end{align}

\end_inset

On the one hand, Eqs.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:k.E"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:k.B"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 simply imply that the fields are perpendicular to the propagation wave-vector,
 i.e.
 the electromagnetic waves are transverse.
 On the other hand, we have Eqs.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:kcrossE"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:kcrossB"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 to be obeyed as well.
 First of all, these imply that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vect k$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $\vect E_{0,\vect k}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vect B_{0,\vect k}$
\end_inset

 
\shape italic
are a set of mutually perpendicular vectors, whose norms have to respect
 the following system of equations:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
k\abs{\vect E_{0,\vect k}}-\omega\abs{\vect B_{0,\vect k}} & =0\\
-\mu_{0}\varepsilon_{m}\omega\abs{\vect E_{0,\vect k}}+k\abs{\vect B_{0,\vect k}} & =0,
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\shape default
which only has a non-zero solution provided the secular determinant is null,
 implying
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
-\mu_{0}\varepsilon_{m}\omega^{2}+k^{2}=0\Rightarrow\omega=\pm\frac{1}{\sqrt{\mu_{0}\varepsilon_{m}}}k\label{eq:omegavsk}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and, hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{m}=1/\sqrt{\mu_{0}\varepsilon_{m}}$
\end_inset

 is the phase velocity of the plane-wave inside the propagation medium.
 In those conditions, the system above yields 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\abs{\vect B_{0,\vect k}}=\frac{1}{v_{m}}\abs{\vect E_{0,\vect k}}.\label{eq:RelationBetweentheamplitudes}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The situation is represented by the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

right-hand rule
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 depicted in Fig.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:1"

\end_inset


\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset

a).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Pictures/EMPlaneWave.pdf
	lyxscale 20
	scale 60

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:1"

\end_inset

a) Depiction of the vector character of the electric and magnetic field
 components of a progressing electromagnetic wave with a wave-vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\vect k$
\end_inset

 in three-dimensional space.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Energy-Density of the Electromagnetic Field
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Intuitively, one understands that there must be energy stored in a set up
 electromagnetic field, since there was work done by conservative forces
 in order to place all the electric charges and currents that generate those
 fields.
 The question is then: How do we calculate that potential energy, by knowing
 the field configurations? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Electric Component
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to answer this questions, we start by remembering that we may define
 electric potential 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}\left(\vect r,t\right)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vect E\left(\vect r,t\right)=-\nabla\mathcal{V}\left(\vect r,t\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The electrostatic potential energy associated to an arbitrary distribution
 of free charges, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{f}\left(\vect r,t\right)$
\end_inset

, which is responsible by the existence of the field, is given by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{U}_{e}\left(\vect r,t\right)=\frac{1}{2}\int_{\text{All Space}}d\vect r\left\{ \rho_{f}\left(\vect r,t\right)\mathcal{V}\left(\vect r,t\right)\right\} =\frac{1}{2}\int_{\text{All Space}}d\vect r\left\{ \nabla\cdot\vect D\left(\vect r,t\right)\mathcal{V}\left(\vect r,t\right)\right\} ,\label{eq:ElectrostaticEnergy}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where we used Gauss's law to write the charge density in the last equality.
 The factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\nicefrac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

 comes from the double counting of the pairs of charges (see
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "key-2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 This being said, we remind ourselves that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\nabla\cdot\left(\vect V\left(\vect r\right)f\left(\vect r\right)\right)=\nabla\cdot\left(\vect V\left(\vect r\right)\right)f\left(\vect r\right)+\vect V\left(\vect r\right)\nabla\left(f\left(\vect r\right)\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which together with Eq.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ElectrostaticEnergy"

\end_inset

, yields the following result:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathcal{U}_{e}\left(\vect r,t\right) & =\frac{1}{2}\int_{\text{All Space}}d\vect r\left\{ \nabla\cdot\left(\vect D\left(\vect r,t\right)\mathcal{V}\left(\vect r,t\right)\right)\right\} +\frac{1}{2}\int_{\text{All Space}}d\vect r\vect D\left(\vect r,t\right)\cdot\vect E\left(\vect r,t\right)\\
 & =\frac{1}{2}\varoiint_{\text{S}_{\infty}}d\vect S\cdot\left\{ \vect E\left(\vect r,t\right)\mathcal{V}\left(\vect r,t\right)\right\} +\frac{1}{2}\int_{\text{All Space}}d\vect r\vect D\left(\vect r,t\right)\cdot\vect E\left(\vect r,t\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

If one assumes, as usual, that all the fields die out at infinity, we arrive
 at the usual expression for the electrostatic energy of a field configuration:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{U}_{e}\left(\vect r,t\right)=\frac{1}{2}\int_{\text{All Space}}d\vect r\vect D\left(\vect r,t\right)\cdot\vect E\left(\vect r,t\right)=\frac{\varepsilon_{0}\varepsilon_{m}}{2}\int_{\text{All Space}}d\vect r\abs{\vect E\left(\vect r,t\right)}^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

thus giving an energy density of
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u_{e}\left(\vect r,t\right)=\frac{\varepsilon_{0}\varepsilon_{m}}{2}\abs{\vect E\left(\vect r,t\right)}^{2}.\label{eq:ElectrostaticEnergyDensity}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The same expression can be obtained by the usual argument of the work done
 during an infinitesimal variation of the the local electric charge density.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Magnetic Component
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is a well-known fact that a static magnetic field produces a (Lorentz)
 force on any moving electric charge, that is perpendicular to its velocity.
 Hence, such forces will never do any work on the moving charges.
 However, there is a way for a magnetic field to contribute to the total
 energy of the system: by causing electric fields due to magnetic induction.
 In other words, to onset a magnetic field in space, one needs to perform
 work in building-up the current as a pay-off to the electromotive force
 generated by self-induction.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to calculate that energy, we may start from the usual expression
 for the power (rate of energy transfer) needed to create a current 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 going around an arbitrary circuit, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

, as drawn in Fig.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:1"

\end_inset


\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset

b).
 This goes as follows
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{dW\left(t\right)}{dt}=I(t)\varepsilon_{\text{EMF}}\left(t\right)=-I\left(t\right)\frac{d}{dt}\left\{ \iint_{S_{\mathcal{C}}}\vect B\left(\vect r,t\right)\cdot\vect{dS}\right\} .
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Now, we may proceed by recognizing that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vect B\left(\vect r,t\right)=\nabla\times\vect A\left(\vect r,t\right)$
\end_inset

 and, using Stokes' Theorem, we arrive at the following expression:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{dW\left(t\right)}{dt}=I\left(t\right)\frac{d}{dt}\left\{ \ointclockwise_{\mathcal{C}}\vect A\left(\vect r,t\right)\cdot\vect{dl}\right\} ,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

or, using the Biot-Savart's Law for the vector potential, we arrive at the
 following expression:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{dW\left(t\right)}{dt} & =-\frac{4\pi}{\mu_{0}}I\left(t\right)\frac{d}{dt}\left\{ I\left(t\right)\ointclockwise_{\mathcal{C}}\ointclockwise_{\mathcal{C}}\frac{1}{\abs{\vect r-\vect r'}}\vect{dl}'\cdot\vect{dl}\right\} \nonumber \\
 & =-\frac{d}{dt}\left\{ \frac{2\pi}{\mu_{0}}I^{2}\left(t\right)\ointclockwise_{\mathcal{C}}\ointclockwise_{\mathcal{C}}\frac{1}{\abs{\vect r-\vect r'}}\vect{dl}'\cdot\vect{dl}\right\} \nonumber \\
 & =-\frac{d}{dt}\left\{ \frac{1}{2}\ointclockwise_{\mathcal{C}}\vect A\left(\vect r,t\right)\cdot I\left(t\right)\vect{dl}\right\} =-\frac{d}{dt}\left\{ \frac{1}{2}\ointclockwise_{\mathcal{C}}\vect A\left(\vect r,t\right)\cdot\vect I\left(t\right)\right\} .\label{eq:WorkDerivative}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Apart from an irrelevant current, Eq.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:WorkDerivative"

\end_inset

 implies that the magnetic energy stored by a circuit having a current 
\begin_inset Formula $\vect I\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 is given as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{U}_{\text{mag}}^{\mathcal{C}}=-W\left(t\right)=\frac{1}{2}\ointclockwise_{\mathcal{C}}\vect A\left(\vect r,t\right)\cdot\vect I\left(t\right).\label{eq:MagEnergy_Circuit}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Note that Eq.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:MagEnergy_Circuit"

\end_inset

, despite being written in terms of the vector potential, it is a gauge-invarian
t quantity as summing the gradient of an arbitrary differentiable function
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\vect A\left(\vect r,t\right)$
\end_inset

 would yield a zero contribution to the integral.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If, instead of a line circuit, we had a volume current density in the system,
 our expression for the magnetic energy could be obtained by a simple generaliza
tion of Eq.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:MagEnergy_Circuit"

\end_inset

.
 I.e., we notice that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{U}_{\text{mag}}^{\mathcal{C}}=\frac{1}{2}\ointclockwise_{\mathcal{C}}\vect A\left(\vect r,t\right)\cdot\vect I\left(t\right)=\frac{1}{2}\iint_{S_{T}}d^{2}\vect R\ointclockwise_{\mathcal{C}}\delta^{2}\left(\vect R-\vect R_{\mathcal{C}}\right)\vect A\left(\vect R,t\right)\cdot\vect J\left(\vect R,t\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and, if we relax the constraint of the circuit given by the Dirac-
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

, we arrive at the following volume expression
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{U}_{\text{mag}}\left(t\right)=\frac{1}{2}\iiint_{\text{All Space}}d\vect r\vect A\left(\vect r,t\right)\cdot\vect J\left(\vect r,t\right).
\]

\end_inset

This equation can be further simplified by using Amp√®re's Law (without the
 displacement current
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Lacks argument??
\end_layout

\end_inset

) and write 
\begin_inset Formula $\vect J\left(\vect r,t\right)=\mu_{0}^{-1}\nabla\times\vect B\left(\vect r,t\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This gives
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{U}_{\text{mag}}\left(t\right)=\frac{1}{2\mu_{0}}\iiint_{\text{All Space}}d\vect r\vect A\left(\vect r,t\right)\cdot\nabla\times\vect B\left(\vect r,t\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and together with the result,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\nabla\cdot\left(\vect V_{1}\times\vect V_{2}\right)=\vect V_{2}\cdot\nabla\times\left(\vect V_{1}\right)-\vect V_{1}\cdot\nabla\times\left(\vect V_{2}\right),\label{eq:DivCross}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

we arrive at 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{U}_{\text{mag}}\left(t\right)=\frac{1}{2\mu_{0}}\iiint_{\text{All Space}}d\vect r\nabla\cdot\left\{ \vect A\left(\vect r,t\right)\times\vect B\left(\vect r,t\right)\right\} +\frac{1}{2\mu_{0}}\iiint_{\text{All Space}}d\vect r\vect B\left(\vect r,t\right)\cdot\nabla\times\vect A\left(\vect r,t\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Using the Divergence's Theorem, together with the assumption that the fields
 decay to zero very far away from all the currents, we arrive at the following
 expression:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{U}_{\text{mag}}\left(t\right)=\frac{1}{2\mu_{0}}\iiint_{\text{All Space}}d\vect r\abs{\vect B\left(\vect r,t\right)}^{2},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

thus yielding a magnetic energy density of
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u_{\text{mag}}\left(\vect r,t\right)=\frac{1}{2\mu_{0}}\abs{\vect B\left(\vect r,t\right)}^{2}.\label{eq:MagEnergyDensity}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Poynting's Theorem and Electromagnetic Energy Propagation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Both Eqs.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ElectrostaticEnergyDensity"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:MagEnergyDensity"

\end_inset

 may be obtained in a more formal manner, using the very definition of the
 work done by a force.
 More precisely, the work done on an element of charge, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\left(\vect r,t\right)d\vect r$
\end_inset

, by the full electromagnetic force while it moves an infinitesimal distance
 
\begin_inset Formula $d\vect l$
\end_inset

 is given by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\vect F_{\text{EM}}\cdot d\vect l & =\rho\left(\vect r,t\right)d\vect r\left[\vect E\left(\vect r,t\right)+\vect B\left(\vect r,t\right)\times\vect v\left(\vect r,t\right)\right]\cdot d\vect l\nonumber \\
 & =\rho\left(\vect r,t\right)d\vect r\left[\vect E\left(\vect r,t\right)+\vect B\left(\vect r,t\right)\times\vect v\left(\vect r,t\right)\right]\cdot\vect v\left(\vect r,t\right)dt\label{eq:WorkEMForces}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\vect v\left(\vect r,t\right)$
\end_inset

 is the local instantaneous velocity of the charge element.
 From Eq.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:WorkEMForces"

\end_inset

 it is trivial to obtain that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\vect F_{\text{EM}}\cdot d\vect l=\rho\left(\vect r,t\right)\vect E\left(\vect r,t\right)\cdot\vect v\left(\vect r,t\right)d\vect rdt=\vect E\cdot\vect J\left(\vect r,t\right)d\vect rdt\label{eq:WorkEMForces_2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and, if one is interested in the work done on a finite volume of three-dimension
al space, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

, we arrive at the following expression:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
W_{t\to t+dt}=\iiint_{\mathcal{V}}\left[\vect E\left(\vect r,t\right)\cdot\vect J\left(\vect r,t\right)d\vect r\right]dt.\label{eq:WorkEMForces_2-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, we wish to express Eq.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:WorkEMForces_2-1"

\end_inset

 only in terms of the electromagnetic fields in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

, which can be done by using Amp√®re's law with the displacement current,
 i.e.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\nabla\times\vect B\left(\vect r,t\right)=\mu_{0}\vect J\left(\vect r,t\right)+\mu_{0}\varepsilon_{m}\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\vect E\left(\vect r,t\right).\label{eq:AmpereLawwithDisplacementCurrent}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Hence, we get the following two terms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
W_{t\to t+dt}=\left\{ \frac{1}{\mu_{0}}\iiint_{\mathcal{V}}\left[\vect E\left(\vect r,t\right)\cdot\nabla\times\vect B\left(\vect r,t\right)d\vect r\right]-\varepsilon_{m}\iiint_{\mathcal{V}}\left[\vect E\left(\vect r,t\right)\cdot\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\vect E\left(\vect r,t\right)d\vect r\right]\right\} dt\label{eq:WorkEMForces_2-1-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

or, using also the identity of Eq.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DivCross"

\end_inset

 and turning the last term into a full time partial derivative, we get
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
W_{t\to t+dt} & =\left\{ \frac{1}{\mu_{0}}\iiint_{\mathcal{V}}\nabla\cdot\left[\vect E\left(\vect r,t\right)\times\vect B\left(\vect r,t\right)d\vect r\right]+\frac{1}{\mu_{0}}\iiint_{\mathcal{V}}\left[\vect B\left(\vect r,t\right)\cdot\nabla\times\vect E\left(\vect r,t\right)d\vect r\right]\right.\nonumber \\
 & \qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\left.-\frac{\varepsilon_{m}}{2}\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\iiint_{\mathcal{V}}\abs{\vect E\left(\vect r,t\right)}^{2}d\vect r\right\} dt\nonumber \\
 & =\left\{ \frac{1}{\mu_{0}}\varoiint_{S_{\mathcal{V}}}\left[\vect E\left(\vect r,t\right)\times\vect B\left(\vect r,t\right)\right]\cdot d\vect S\right.\nonumber \\
 & \qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\quad\qquad\left.-\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\left\{ \frac{\varepsilon_{m}}{2}\iiint_{\mathcal{V}}\abs{\vect E\left(\vect r,t\right)}^{2}d\vect r+\frac{1}{2\mu_{0}}\iiint_{\mathcal{V}}\abs{\vect B\left(\vect r,t\right)}^{2}d\vect r\right\} \right\} dt,\label{eq:PoyintingTheorem}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where we made use of both Faraday's Law (
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\times\vect E\left(\vect r,t\right)=-\nicefrac{\partial}{\partial t}\vect B\left(\vect r,t\right)$
\end_inset

) and the Divergence's Theorem in the first integral.
 This last equation encapsulates what is named Poynting's Theorem and it
 basically tells us that the rate of change of the energy inside a given
 volume can be due to either the intrinsic time variation of both fields
 (second term) or to the flux of the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{0}^{-1}\vect E\times\vect B$
\end_inset

 through the surface.
 If we consider the volume 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

 as an arbitrary volume containing all charges and currents in the system,
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $dW=0$
\end_inset

 and we arrive at the following continuity equation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\left\{ \frac{\varepsilon_{m}}{2}\abs{\vect E\left(\vect r,t\right)}^{2}+\frac{1}{2\mu_{0}}\abs{\vect B\left(\vect r,t\right)}^{2}\right\} =\nabla\cdot\left(\frac{1}{\mu_{0}}\vect E\left(\vect r,t\right)\times\vect B\left(\vect r,t\right)\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This last equation simply restates that there is an energy density (per
 unit volume) associated to an electromagnetic field, given as before by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u_{\text{EM}}\left(\vect r,t\right)=\frac{\varepsilon_{m}}{2}\abs{\vect E\left(\vect r,t\right)}^{2}+\frac{1}{2\mu_{0}}\abs{\vect B\left(\vect r,t\right)}^{2}\label{eq:EMEnergyDensity}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and there is also a vector field
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\vect S\left(\vect r,t\right)=\frac{1}{\mu_{0}}\vect E\left(\vect r,t\right)\times\vect B\left(\vect r,t\right),\label{eq:Poyinting}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which stands for the directed energy density transferred by the electromagnetic
 field across space.
 The vector in Eq.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Poyinting"

\end_inset

 is known as the Poynting vector.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Energy Transported by a Plane Electromagnetic Wave
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, we are in possession of all the tools to calculate the energy transport
ed by an electromagnetic plane-wave, when traveling through a dielectric
 medium.
 On the one hand, we have the fields of the wave
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\vect E_{\overrightarrow{k}}\left(\overrightarrow{r},t\right) & =\vect E_{0,\overrightarrow{k}}e^{i\left(\overrightarrow{k}\cdot\overrightarrow{r}-\omega t\right)}\label{eq:ElectricFieldPlaneWave-1}\\
\vect B_{\overrightarrow{k}}\left(\overrightarrow{r},t\right) & =\vect B_{0,\overrightarrow{k}}e^{i\left(\overrightarrow{k}\cdot\overrightarrow{r}-\omega t\right)},\label{eq:MagneticFieldPlaneWave-1}
\end{align}

\end_inset

with the relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\vect B_{0,\vect k}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{\mu_{0}\varepsilon_{m}}}\hat{\mathbf{k}}\times\vect E_{0,\vect k}$
\end_inset

, and also the general expression for the Poynting vector, which allows
 us to calculate the energy transport across space due to electromagnetic
 fields, i.e.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\vect S\left(\vect r,t\right)=\frac{1}{\mu_{0}}\vect E\left(\vect r,t\right)\times\vect B\left(\vect r,t\right).\label{eq:Poyinting-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Despite having these expression, one must be careful when calculating the
 Poynting vector associated to the fields of Eqs.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ElectricFieldPlaneWave-1"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:MagneticFieldPlaneWave-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, for they are complex representations of the real fields.
 Aware of this fact and using Eqs.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ElectricFieldPlaneWave-1"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Poyinting-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we arrive at the following pointing vector for the electromagnetic plane-wave:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\vect S\left(\vect r,t\right)=\frac{1}{\mu_{0}}\vect E_{0,\overrightarrow{k}}\times\vect B_{0,\overrightarrow{k}}\cos^{2}\left(\vect k\cdot\vect r-\omega t\right)=\frac{1}{\mu_{0}v_{m}}\abs{\vect E_{0,\overrightarrow{k}}}^{2}\cos^{2}\left(\vect k\cdot\vect r-\omega t\right)\mathbf{\hat{k}}.\label{eq:Poyinting-1-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The intensity of the wave is usually defined as the average of 
\begin_inset Formula $\abs{\vect S\left(\vect r,t\right)}$
\end_inset

 over a time period, as the detection devices usually do not have enough
 resolution to observe the space and time variations implied in Eq.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Poyinting-1-1"

\end_inset

.
 Hence, we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{I}_{\perp}=\frac{\omega}{2\pi}\frac{1}{\mu_{0}v_{m}}\abs{\vect E_{0,\overrightarrow{k}}}^{2}\int_{t}^{t+\frac{2\pi}{\omega}}d\tau\cos^{2}\left(\vect k\cdot\vect r-\omega\tau\right)=\frac{1}{2\mu_{0}v_{m}}\abs{\vect E_{0,\overrightarrow{k}}}^{2}.\label{eq:IntensityPlaneWave}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

If the incidence is at a certain angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 with respect to the surface's normal, we will have an effective intensity
 which is simply,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{I}=\frac{1}{2\mu_{0}v_{m}}\abs{\vect E_{0,\overrightarrow{k}}}^{2}\cos\alpha.\label{eq:IntensityPlaneWave-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Boundary Conditions of Electromagnetic Fields across Conducting Interfaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we will derive the boundary conditions associated to electric
 and magnetic fields, when they cross a boundary between two dielectrics
 with different refractive indexes, 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{2}$
\end_inset

, and are separated by a conducting surface with a complex conductivity,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{S}=\sigma'+i\sigma''$
\end_inset

.
 As usual, these conditions can be derived directly from Maxwell's Equations
 in their integral form, which we restate here in non-magnetic dielectric
 media:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size large
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{cc}
\varoiint_{S_{\mathcal{V}}}\vect D\left(\vect r,t\right)\cdot d\vect S= & \iiint_{\mathcal{V}}\rho\left(\vect r,t\right)d\vect r\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\\
\\
\varoiint_{S_{\mathcal{V}}}\vect B\left(\vect r,t\right)\cdot d\vect S= & 0\qquad\qquad\qquad\quad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\\
\\
\quad\ointclockwise_{\mathcal{C}}\vect E\left(\vect r,t\right)\cdot d\vect S= & -\iiint d\vect r\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\vect B\left(\vect r,t\right)\quad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\\
\\
\quad\ointclockwise_{\mathcal{C}}\vect B\left(\vect r,t\right)\cdot d\vect S= & \mu_{0}\iiint d\vect r\vect J\left(\vect r,t\right)-\mu_{0}\iiint d\vect r\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\vect D\left(\vect r,t\right)
\end{array}\label{eq:IntegralMaxwellEquations}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\size default
The first two equations yield the discontinuity (continuity) of the electric
 (magnetic) field across the boundary.
 In order to see that, let us consider a pillbox surface, as depicted in
 Fig
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:BoundaryConditions"

\end_inset


\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset

a).
 Since there are no free charges on the interface, and the pillbox has an
 arbitrary shape, we can see immediately that the following conditions must
 hold at the interface:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\begin{array}{cc}
\vect D_{1}^{\perp} & =\vect D_{2}^{\perp}+\rho_{S}\left(\vect r,t\right)\\
\vect B_{1}^{\perp} & =\vect B_{2}^{\perp}
\end{array}\Longrightarrow\begin{array}{cc}
\varepsilon_{1}\vect E_{1}^{\perp} & =\varepsilon_{2}\vect E_{2}^{\perp}+\rho_{S}\left(\vect r,t\right)\\
\vect B_{1}^{\perp} & =\vect B_{2}^{\perp}
\end{array},
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{S}$
\end_inset

 is the non-homogeneous free charge density that is induced in the surface
 by the parallel electric field.
 If we have an ohmic conducting interface, there will be a surface current
 flowing in it, which is driven by the electric field at the boundary, i.e.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vect K\left(\vect r,t\right)=\sigma_{S}\vect E\left(\vect r,t\right)=\left[\sigma'+i\sigma''\right]\vect E\left(\vect r,t\right),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\vect r$
\end_inset

 is restricted to be on the interface.
 Besides this induced current, by continuity, we also have an induced surface
 charge density which is related to this current.
 This can be calculated as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\rho_{S}\left(y,z,t\right) & =\frac{\partial}{\partial y}K_{y}\left(y,z,t\right)+\frac{\partial}{\partial z}K_{z}\left(y,z,t\right)\\
\rho_{S}\left(y,z,t\right) & =\sigma_{S}\left\{ \frac{\partial}{\partial y}\int_{0}^{t}E_{y}\left(0,y,z,\tau\right)d\tau+\frac{\partial}{\partial z}\int_{0}^{t}E_{z}\left(0,y,z,\tau\right)d\tau\right\} ,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

if the interface is placed at the 
\begin_inset Formula $(x=0)$
\end_inset

-plane.
 Assuming that our electric field is a plane wave of the kind (with an adiabatic
 connection from 
\begin_inset Formula $t\to-\infty$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vect E\left(x,y,z,t\right)=\lim_{\gamma\to0^{+}}\vect E_{0}e^{i\left(\vect k\cdot\vect r-\omega t+\phi\right)-\gamma t},
\]

\end_inset

it will generate an induced surface current given as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\rho_{S}\left(y,z,t\right) & =\lim_{\gamma\to0^{+}}i\sigma_{S}\left\{ E_{0y}k_{y}e^{i\vect k\cdot\vect r}+E_{0z}k_{z}e^{i\vect k\cdot\vect r}\right\} \int_{-\infty}^{t}e^{-i\omega t-\gamma t}\\
 & =-\lim_{\gamma\to0^{+}}\frac{\sigma_{S}}{\omega+i\gamma}\left\{ E_{0y}k_{y}e^{i\vect k\cdot\vect r+i\phi}+E_{0z}k_{z}e^{i\vect k\cdot\vect r+i\phi}\right\} \left\{ e^{-i\omega t-\gamma t}\right\} \\
 & =\frac{\sigma_{S}}{\omega}\vect E^{\parallel}\left(0,y,z,t\right)\cdot\vect k,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

hence, our electric fields' boundary conditions are given as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varepsilon_{1}\vect E_{1}^{\perp}=\varepsilon_{2}\vect E_{2}^{\perp}+\frac{\sigma_{S}}{\omega}\vect E_{\vect k,0}^{\parallel}\cdot\vect k\label{eq:SurfaceCurrent}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In these conditions we may consider the two cases depicted in Fig.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:BoundaryConditions"

\end_inset


\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset

b), where the circuits crossing the interface are parallel (blue) or perpendicul
ar (red) to the flow of the surface current.
 Now, using the two last expressions of Eq.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:IntegralMaxwellEquations"

\end_inset

, we arrive at the following expressions boundary conditions in the presence
 of a conducting surface between the two dielectrics:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\begin{array}{cc}
\vect E_{1}^{\parallel} & =\vect E_{2}^{\parallel}\end{array}
\end{align}

\end_inset

and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\begin{array}{cc}
 & \vect B_{1}^{\parallel}=\vect B_{2}^{\parallel}\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\text{when parallel to the current}\qquad\\
 & \vect B_{1}^{\parallel}=\vect B_{2}^{\parallel}+\mu_{0}\left[\sigma'+i\sigma''\right]\vect E^{\parallel}\left(\vect r,t\right)\text{ when perpendicular to the current}
\end{array}.
\end{align}

\end_inset

In a more condensed notation, we have the following boundary conditions
 for the parallel components of the magnetic field:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\vect B_{1}^{\parallel}=\vect B_{2}^{\parallel}+\mu_{0}\left[\sigma'+i\sigma''\right]\mathbf{\hat{n}}\times\vect E^{\parallel}\left(\vect r,t\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Pictures/pillbox.png
	lyxscale 20
	scale 27

\end_inset


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Pictures/squarecircuit.png
	lyxscale 20
	scale 27

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:BoundaryConditions"

\end_inset

a) Pillbox Surface traversing the interface between the two dielectric media.
 b) Square circuit used to derive the boundary conditions for the parallel
 components.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Fresnel Equations for a Conducting Interface between Two Dielectric Media
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we will use the toolbox developed for electromagnetic plane
 waves to study the reflectance, transmittance and absorbance of electromagnetic
 waves when they hit a conducting interface between two dielectrics at an
 angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ensuremath{\theta_{i}}}$
\end_inset

.
 The polarization of our incident plane-wave is arbitrary but, as usual,
 it is helpful to decompose it into two orthogonal linearly-polarized components
 ‚Äî 
\shape slanted
Transverse Magnetic
\shape default
 (TM) and 
\shape slanted
Transverse Electric
\shape default
 (TE).
 These two situations are depicted in Fig.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:BoundaryConditions-1"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Pictures/TMPolarization.png
	lyxscale 50
	scale 45

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\qquad$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Pictures/TEPolarization.png
	lyxscale 50
	scale 45

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:BoundaryConditions-1"

\end_inset

Scheme of the Transverse Magnetic (left panel) and Transverse Electric (right
 panel) setups.
 The cartesian system of coordinated we will be using is represented, with
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

-axis being defined as out-of-plane.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In all our future calculations, our final aims will be to calculate the
 reflected and transmitted intensities, normalized by the incident ones.
 These quantities can be written in terms of the field amplitudes of each
 wave as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{T}\left(\theta_{i}\right)=\frac{\frac{\cos\varphi}{v_{2}}\abs{\vect E_{t}}^{2}}{\frac{\cos\theta}{v_{1}}\abs{\vect E_{i}}^{2}}=\frac{n_{2}\cos\varphi\abs{\vect E_{t}}^{2}}{n_{1}\cos\theta\abs{\vect E_{i}}^{2}}\label{eq:Transmittance}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{R}\left(\theta_{i}\right)=\frac{\frac{1}{v_{1}}\abs{\vect E_{r}}^{2}}{\frac{1}{v_{1}}\abs{\vect E_{i}}^{2}}=\frac{\abs{\vect E_{t}}^{2}}{\abs{\vect E_{i}}^{2}},\label{eq:Transmittance-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{1}=\sqrt{\varepsilon_{1}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{2}=\sqrt{\varepsilon_{2}}$
\end_inset

 are the refractive indexes of the respective dielectric medium.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Besides reflexion and transmission, we are also expected to have dissipation
 in the conducting boundary.
 This can be described by an absorbance (per unit area) defined as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{A}\left(\theta_{i}\right)=1-\mathcal{R}\left(\theta_{i}\right)-\mathcal{T}\left(\theta_{i}\right).\label{eq:Absorbance}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Refraction of Transverse Magnetic (TM) Polarized Light
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will begin by dealing with the case of TM polarization.
 In this case, the electric field is always in the plane of incidence and
 so will be the surface current.
 Hence, the (phasor-represented) plane-waves involved can be written as
 follows:
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note that we are using the cartesian system of coordinated defined in Fig.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:BoundaryConditions-1"

\end_inset

 and the conducting surface is considered to be located at the plane defined
 by 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

.
 This choice involves no loss of generality.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Incident Wave:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\vect E_{i}\left(\overrightarrow{r},t\right) & =\abs{\vect E_{i}}e^{i\left(\overrightarrow{k}_{i}\cdot\overrightarrow{r}-\omega t\right)}\left[-\sin\theta_{i}\mathbf{\hat{x}}+\cos\theta_{i}\mathbf{\hat{y}}\right]\label{eq:ElectricFieldPlaneWave-1-1}\\
\vect B_{i}\left(\overrightarrow{r},t\right) & =\abs{\vect B_{i}}e^{i\left(\overrightarrow{k}_{i}\cdot\overrightarrow{r}-\omega t\right)}\hat{\mathbf{z}},\label{eq:MagneticFieldPlaneWave-1-1}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Reflected Wave:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\vect E_{r}\left(\overrightarrow{r},t\right) & =-\abs{\vect E_{r}}e^{i\left(\overrightarrow{k}_{r}\cdot\overrightarrow{r}-\omega t+\phi_{r}\right)}\left[\sin\theta_{r}\mathbf{\hat{x}}+\cos\theta_{r}\mathbf{\hat{y}}\right]\label{eq:ElectricFieldPlaneWave-1-1-1}\\
\vect B_{r}\left(\overrightarrow{r},t\right) & =\abs{\vect B_{r}}e^{i\left(\overrightarrow{k}_{r}\cdot\overrightarrow{r}-\omega t+\phi_{r}\right)}\hat{\mathbf{z}},\label{eq:MagneticFieldPlaneWave-1-1-1}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Transmitted Wave:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\vect E_{t}\left(\overrightarrow{r},t\right) & =\abs{\vect E_{t}}e^{i\left(\overrightarrow{k}_{t}\cdot\overrightarrow{r}-\omega t+\phi_{t}\right)}\left[-\sin\varphi\mathbf{\hat{x}}+\cos\varphi\mathbf{\hat{y}}\right]\label{eq:ElectricFieldPlaneWave-1-1-1-1}\\
\vect B_{t}\left(\overrightarrow{r},t\right) & =\abs{\vect B_{t}}e^{i\left(\overrightarrow{k}_{t}\cdot\overrightarrow{r}-\omega t+\phi_{t}\right)}\hat{\mathbf{z}},\label{eq:MagneticFieldPlaneWave-1-1-1-1}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
The frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is obviously the same for all three cases, as we which the boundary conditions
 to be satisfied at all times.
 The same kind of reasoning applied to the space-dependence gives rise to
 Snell's Laws
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\theta_{r}=\theta_{i}\equiv\theta,
\]

\end_inset

(from the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vect k_{i}=\frac{\omega}{v_{1}}\left(\cos\theta_{i}\mathbf{\hat{x}}+\sin\theta_{i}\mathbf{\hat{y}}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vect k_{r}=\frac{\omega}{v_{1}}\left(-\cos\theta_{i}\mathbf{\hat{x}}+\sin\theta_{i}\mathbf{\hat{y}}\right)$
\end_inset

) and also 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n_{1}\sin\theta=n_{2}\sin\varphi,
\]

\end_inset

coming from 
\begin_inset Formula $\vect k_{t}=\frac{\omega}{v_{2}}\left(\cos\varphi\mathbf{\hat{x}}+\sin\varphi\mathbf{\hat{y}}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, we may now use the boundary conditions defined in the previous
 section and impose them at the interface between the two media.
 For the electric field components these conditions go as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\abs{\vect E_{i}}\cos\theta_{i}-\abs{\vect E_{r}}e^{i\phi_{r}}\cos\theta_{r} & =\abs{\vect E_{t}}e^{i\phi_{t}}\cos\varphi\label{eq:TECondition1}\\
\abs{\vect E_{i}}\sin\theta_{i}+\abs{\vect E_{r}}e^{i\phi_{r}}\sin\theta_{r} & =\abs{\vect E_{t}}e^{i\phi_{t}}\left\{ \frac{\varepsilon_{2}}{\varepsilon_{1}}\sin\varphi+\frac{\sigma_{S}}{2\omega\varepsilon_{1}}\abs{\vect k_{t}}\sin2\varphi\right\} \label{eq:TECondition2}
\end{align}

\end_inset

and noting that 
\begin_inset Formula $\abs{\vect k_{t}}=\omega/v_{m}=\omega n_{2}c^{-1}$
\end_inset

, we get
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\abs{\vect E_{i}}\cos\theta_{i}-\abs{\vect E_{r}}e^{i\phi_{r}}\cos\theta_{r} & =\abs{\vect E_{t}}e^{i\phi_{t}}\cos\varphi\label{eq:TECondition1-1}\\
\abs{\vect E_{i}}\sin\theta_{i}+\abs{\vect E_{r}}e^{i\phi_{r}}\sin\theta_{r} & =\abs{\vect E_{t}}e^{i\phi_{t}}\left\{ \left(\frac{n_{2}}{n_{1}}\right)^{2}\sin\varphi+\frac{n_{2}\sigma_{S}}{2c\varepsilon_{0}n_{1}^{2}}\sin2\varphi\right\} \label{eq:TECondition2-1}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the magnetic field we have a discontinuity due to the surface current,
 which now is in the 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

-axis' direction.
 I.e.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\abs{\vect B_{i}}+\abs{\vect B_{r}}e^{i\phi_{r}}=\abs{\vect B_{t}}e^{i\phi_{t}}+\mu_{0}\sigma_{S}\abs{\vect E_{t}}e^{i\phi_{t}}\cos\varphi.\label{eq:TMCondition3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Now, we must use the expression connecting the magnetic to the electric
 amplitudes of each one of the plane waves to write Eqs.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:TECondition1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:TMCondition3"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 in terms of electric field amplitudes only.
 In other words,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{1}{v_{1}}\abs{\vect E_{i}}+\frac{1}{v_{1}}\abs{\vect E_{r}}e^{i\phi_{r}}=\frac{1}{v_{2}}\abs{\vect E_{t}}e^{i\phi_{t}}+\mu_{0}\sigma_{S}\abs{\vect E_{t}}e^{i\phi_{t}}\cos\varphi,\label{eq:TMCondition3-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

or
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\abs{\vect E_{i}}+\abs{\vect E_{r}}e^{i\phi_{r}}=\left(\frac{n_{2}}{n_{1}}+\frac{\mu_{0}c\sigma_{S}}{n_{1}}\cos\varphi\right)e^{i\phi_{t}}\abs{\vect E_{t}},\label{eq:TMCondition3-1-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is the velocity of light in the vacuum.
 Hence, the linear system which describes the imposition of the interface
 boundary conditions is written as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
\abs{\vect E_{i}}\cos\theta_{i}-\abs{\vect E_{r}}e^{i\phi_{r}}\cos\theta_{r}-\abs{\vect E_{t}}e^{i\phi_{t}}\left\{ \cos\varphi+\frac{\sigma_{S}}{\omega}\sin^{2}\varphi\right\}  & =0\\
\\
\abs{\vect E_{i}}\sin\theta_{i}+\abs{\vect E_{r}}e^{i\phi_{r}}\sin\theta_{r}-\abs{\vect E_{t}}e^{i\phi_{t}}\left\{ \frac{n_{2}}{n_{1}}\sin\theta+\frac{n_{2}\sigma_{S}}{2c\varepsilon_{0}n_{1}^{2}}\sin2\varphi\right\}  & =0\\
\\
\abs{\vect E_{i}}+\abs{\vect E_{r}}e^{i\phi_{r}}-\left(\frac{n_{2}}{n_{1}}+\frac{\mu_{0}c\sigma_{S}}{n_{1}}\cos\varphi\right)e^{i\phi_{t}}\abs{\vect E_{t}} & =0
\end{cases},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

or
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
\cos\theta & -e^{i\phi_{r}}\cos\theta & -e^{i\phi_{t}}\cos\varphi\\
\sin\theta & e^{i\phi_{r}}\sin\theta & -\frac{n_{2}}{n_{1}}e^{i\phi_{t}}\left(\sin\theta+\frac{1}{2}\xi\sin2\varphi\right)\\
1 & e^{i\phi_{r}} & -\frac{n_{2}}{n_{1}}e^{i\phi_{t}}-\xi e^{i\phi_{t}}\cos\varphi
\end{array}\right)\cdot\left(\begin{array}{c}
\abs{\vect E_{i}}\\
\abs{\vect E_{r}}\\
\abs{\vect E_{t}}
\end{array}\right)=\left(\begin{array}{c}
0\\
0\\
0
\end{array}\right),
\]

\end_inset

where we already used Snell's laws and defined 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi=\mu_{0}c\sigma_{S}/n_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 This system only has a non-trivial solution if the secular determinant
 is zero.
 This means that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
-\frac{2\xi\cos(\theta)\cos(\phi)e^{i\left(\phi_{r}+\phi_{t}\right)}\left(n_{1}\sin(\theta)-n_{2}\sin(\phi)\right)}{n_{1}}=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which means that there is only transmission if 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 obey Snell's Law of transmission.
 In this case, our original 
\begin_inset Formula $3\times3$
\end_inset

 system is indeterminate and we can find the transmission and reflexion
 coefficients from just two of the equations.
 For instance,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
\abs{\vect E_{i}}\cos\theta-\abs{\vect E_{r}}\cos\theta e^{i\phi_{r}}-\abs{\vect E_{t}}\cos\varphi e^{i\phi_{t}} & =0\\
\\
\abs{\vect E_{i}}+\abs{\vect E_{r}}e^{i\phi_{r}}-\left(\frac{n_{2}}{n_{1}}+\xi\cos\varphi\right)\abs{\vect E_{t}}e^{i\phi_{t}} & =0
\end{cases},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

meaning that, by summing the two equations as 
\begin_inset Formula $eq_{1}+eq_{2}\times\cos\theta$
\end_inset

), we get the ratio of the transmitted and incident complex electric field
 amplitudes as follows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
2\cos\theta\abs{\vect E_{i}}-\left(\cos\varphi+\left(\frac{n_{2}}{n_{1}}+\xi\right)\cos\theta\right)\abs{\vect E_{t}}e^{i\phi_{t}} & =0\Rightarrow\frac{\abs{\vect E_{t}}e^{i\phi_{t}}}{\abs{\vect E_{i}}}=\frac{2n_{1}\cos\theta}{n_{1}\cos\varphi+\left(n_{2}+n_{1}\xi\right)\cos\theta},\label{eq:TransmissionCoeff}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Additionally, by replacing this back into 
\begin_inset Formula $eq_{1}$
\end_inset

, we get
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\abs{\vect E_{i}}\left(\frac{\left(n_{2}+n_{1}\xi\right)\cos\theta-n_{1}\cos\varphi}{n_{1}\cos\varphi+\left(n_{2}+n_{1}\xi\right)\cos\theta}\right)\cos\theta-\abs{\vect E_{r}}\cos\theta e^{i\phi_{r}}=0
\]

\end_inset

or, alternatively,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\abs{\vect E_{r}}=e^{-i\phi_{r}}\left(\frac{\left(n_{2}+n_{1}\xi\right)\cos\theta-n_{1}\cos\varphi}{n_{1}\cos\varphi+\left(n_{2}+n_{1}\xi\right)\cos\theta}\right)\abs{\vect E_{i}}\Rightarrow\frac{\abs{\vect E_{r}}e^{i\phi_{r}}}{\abs{\vect E_{i}}}=\frac{\left(n_{2}+n_{1}\xi\right)\cos\theta-n_{1}\cos\varphi}{n_{1}\cos\varphi+\left(n_{2}+n_{1}\xi\right)\cos\theta}.\label{eq:ReflectionCoeff}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Note that the previous equations also imply that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{r}=0,\pi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{t}=0$
\end_inset

 if the surface conductivity 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{S}$
\end_inset

 is a real quantity.
 In that case also, from Eqs.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:TransmissionCoeff"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ReflectionCoeff"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 we can get the following reflectance and transmittance:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{R}\left(\theta\right)=\left(\frac{\left(n_{2}+\mu_{0}c\sigma_{S}\right)\cos\theta-n_{1}\cos\varphi}{n_{1}\cos\varphi+\left(n_{2}+\mu_{0}c\sigma_{S}\right)\cos\theta}\right)^{2}
\]

\end_inset

and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{T}\left(\theta\right)=\frac{4n_{1}n_{2}\cos\varphi\cos^{2}\theta}{\cos\theta\left(n_{1}\cos\varphi+\left(n_{2}+\mu_{0}c\sigma_{S}\right)\cos\theta\right)^{2}}.
\]

\end_inset

In terms of only the incidence angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

, and since we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\varphi=\sqrt{1-\left(\nicefrac{n_{1}}{n_{2}}\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\theta},$
\end_inset

we get:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{R}\left(\theta\right)=\left(\frac{\left(n_{2}+\mu_{0}c\sigma_{S}\right)\cos\theta-n_{1}\sqrt{1-\left(\frac{n_{1}}{n_{2}}\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\theta}}{n_{1}\sqrt{1-\left(\frac{n_{1}}{n_{2}}\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\theta}+\left(n_{2}+\mu_{0}c\sigma_{S}\right)\cos\theta}\right)^{2}\label{eq:ReflectanceTM}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{T}\left(\theta\right)=\frac{4n_{1}n_{2}\sqrt{1-\left(\frac{n_{1}}{n_{2}}\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\theta}\cos\theta}{\left(n_{1}\sqrt{1-\left(\frac{n_{1}}{n_{2}}\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\theta}+\left(n_{2}+\mu_{0}c\sigma_{S}\right)\cos\theta\right)^{2}}.\label{eq:TransmitanceTM}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The absorbance can also be calculated directly, yielding:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathcal{A}\left(\theta\right)=1-\mathcal{R}\left(\theta\right)-\mathcal{T}\left(\theta\right) & =\frac{4\mu_{0}c\sigma_{S}n_{1}\cos\theta\sqrt{1-\left(\frac{n_{1}}{n_{2}}\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\theta}}{\left(n_{1}\sqrt{1-\left(\frac{n_{1}}{n_{2}}\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\theta}+\left(n_{2}+\mu_{0}c\sigma_{S}\right)\cos\theta\right){}^{2}}\label{eq:AbsorvanceTM}
\end{align}

\end_inset

which rightfully converges to zero in the limit when 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{S}\to0$
\end_inset

.
 Note that all the calculations above were done assuming a real conductivity
 (i.e.
 purely dissipative).
 Plots of the quantities of Eqs.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ReflectanceTM"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:AbsorvanceTM"

\end_inset

 are shown in Fig.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:NormalIncidenceTM"

\end_inset

, as a function of the angle and for different surface conductivities.
 Note that the optical conductivity of pristine graphene has the following
 expression
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "key-2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sigma\left(\omega,T\right)=\frac{\pi e^{2}}{2\hbar}\left(\frac{1}{2}-\frac{\hbar^{2}\omega^{2}}{72t^{2}}\right)\left(\tanh\left(\frac{\hbar\omega+2\mu}{4k_{\text{B}}T}\right)+\tanh\left(\frac{\hbar\omega-2\mu}{4k_{\text{B}}T}\right)\right),\label{eq:Conductivitygraphene}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $t\approx2.7\text{eV}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is the chemical potential of the graphene (for undoped graphene ‚Äî 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=0$
\end_inset

.).However, more important than the formula itself is to realize that at the
 range of
\emph on
 
\emph default
wavelengths (in air) from 
\begin_inset Formula $100\text{nm}\text{ to }1000\text{nm}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{S}\approx10^{-4}\Omega$
\end_inset

.
 Nevertheless, in the general case, the conductivity of a conducting sheet
 is a complex number.
 In that case, the previous calculations must be done with a little more
 care.
 Namely, we must have the complex reflection coefficient defined as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
re^{i\phi_{r}}=\frac{\left(n_{2}+\mu_{0}c\left(\sigma_{r}+i\sigma_{i}\right)\right)\cos\theta-n_{1}\cos\varphi}{n_{1}\cos\varphi+\left(n_{2}+\mu_{0}c\left(\sigma_{r}+i\sigma_{i}\right)\right)\cos\theta}\label{eq:reflectricioncoeff_complex}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and a complex transmission coefficient
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
te^{i\phi_{t}}=\frac{2n_{1}\cos\theta}{n_{1}\cos\varphi+\left(n_{2}+\mu_{0}c\left(\sigma_{r}+i\sigma_{i}\right)\right)\cos\theta}.\label{eq:transmissioncoeff_comples}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

These expressions yield the following reflectance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathcal{R}_{\text{TM}}\left(\theta\right) & =1-\frac{4n_{1}\cos\theta\sqrt{1-\left(\frac{n_{1}}{n_{2}}\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\theta}\left(c\mu_{0}\sigma_{r}+n_{2}\right)}{c^{2}\mu_{0}^{2}\sigma_{i}^{2}+\left(n_{1}\cos\theta+\left(n_{2}+c\mu_{0}\sigma_{r}\right)\sqrt{1-\left(\frac{n_{1}}{n_{2}}\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\theta}\right)^{2}}
\end{align}

\end_inset

and a transmittance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{T}_{\text{TM}}\left(\theta\right)=\frac{4n_{1}n_{2}\cos\theta\sqrt{1-\left(\frac{n_{1}}{n_{2}}\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\theta}}{c^{2}\mu_{0}^{2}\sigma_{i}^{2}\left(1-\left(\frac{n_{1}}{n_{2}}\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\theta\right)+\left(\left(c\mu_{0}\sigma_{r}+n_{2}\right)\sqrt{1-\left(\frac{n_{1}}{n_{2}}\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\theta}+n_{1}\cos\theta\right){}^{2}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Finally, the energy absorbed by the surface by unit area is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size footnotesize
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{A}_{\text{TM}}\left(\theta\right)=\frac{4c\mu_{0}n_{1}\sigma_{r}\cos\theta\sqrt{1-\left(\frac{n_{1}}{n_{2}}\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\theta}}{\cos^{2}\theta\left(c^{2}\mu_{0}^{2}\left(\sigma_{i}^{2}+\sigma_{r}^{2}\right)+2c\mu_{0}n_{2}\sigma_{r}+n_{2}^{2}\right)+2n_{1}\cos\theta\sqrt{1-\left(\frac{n_{1}}{n_{2}}\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\theta}\left(c\mu_{0}\sigma_{r}+n_{2}\right)+n_{1}^{2}\left(1-\left(\frac{n_{1}}{n_{2}}\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\theta\right)}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Besides these intensity coefficients, the phases of introduced into the
 transmitted and reflected waves are also non-trivial in this case.
 But we do have access to them from Eqs.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:reflectricioncoeff_complex"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:transmissioncoeff_comples"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 These phases can be written as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size footnotesize
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tan\phi_{r}=\frac{2c\mu_{0}n_{1}\sigma_{i}\cos\theta\sqrt{1-\left(\frac{n_{1}}{n_{2}}\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\theta}}{\cos^{2}\theta\left(c^{2}\mu_{0}^{2}\sigma_{i}^{2}+\left(c\mu_{0}\sigma_{r}+n_{2}\right){}^{2}\right)-n_{1}^{2}\left(1-\left(\frac{n_{1}}{n_{2}}\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\theta\right)}\text{ and \tan\phi_{t}=-\frac{c\mu_{0}\sigma_{i}\cos\theta}{\cos\theta\left(c\mu_{0}\sigma_{r}+n_{2}\right)+n_{1}\sqrt{1-\left(\frac{n_{1}}{n_{2}}\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\theta}}.}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\size default
Finally, we can assume that our sheet of graphene has a complex surface
 conductivity as given in
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "key-2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, i.e.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{r}\left(\omega,\mu,T\right)=\frac{\pi e^{2}}{2\hbar}\left(\frac{1}{2}-\frac{\hbar^{2}\omega^{2}}{72t^{2}}\right)\left(\tanh\left(\frac{\hbar\omega+2\mu}{4k_{\text{B}}T}\right)+\tanh\left(\frac{\hbar\omega-2\mu}{4k_{\text{B}}T}\right)\right),\label{eq:RealConductGraphene}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{i}\left(\omega,\mu,T\right)=\frac{2\mu e^{2}}{\hbar^{2}\omega}\left(1-\frac{2\mu^{2}}{9t^{2}}\right)-\frac{e^{2}}{2\hbar}\log\left(\abs{\frac{\hbar\omega+2\mu}{\hbar\omega-2\mu}}\right)-\frac{e^{2}}{72\hbar}\left(\frac{\hbar\omega}{t}\right)^{2}\log\left(\abs{\frac{\hbar\omega+2\mu}{\hbar\omega-2\mu}}\right).\label{eq:ImageGrapheneConductivity}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Note that, in the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\to0$
\end_inset

, the conductivity becomes purely real for a finite excitation frequency.
 Hence, let us assume a positive doping of the order of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\approx0.2$
\end_inset

eV, which would be compatible with a doping with electron acceptors, like
 oxygen atoms.
 Even in that case, the effect of the imaginary part is irrelevant in when
 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is an optical frequency.
 In Fig.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:ObliqueIncidence"

\end_inset

, we depict 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{\text{TM}}\left(\theta\right)$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}_{\text{TM}}\left(\theta\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}_{\text{TM}}\left(\theta\right)$
\end_inset

 for a polarized wave with 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=500\text{nm}$
\end_inset

, using Eqs.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:RealConductGraphene"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ImageGrapheneConductivity"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for the optical conductivity of the graphene sheet.
 More interesting is to look at the limit of normal incidence and calculate
 what is the effect of a single graphene layer on top of a glass surface
 in what concerns the reflectance and transmittance of the interface.
 In this case, we have the following analytical expressions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{R}\left(\theta=0\text{¬∫}\right)=\frac{c^{2}\mu_{0}^{2}\sigma_{i}^{2}+\left(c\mu_{0}\sigma_{r}+n_{2}-n_{1}\right){}^{2}}{c^{2}\mu_{0}^{2}\sigma_{i}^{2}+\left(c\mu_{0}\sigma_{r}+n_{1}+n_{2}\right){}^{2}}\label{eq:ReflectanceNormal}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{T}\left(\theta=0\text{¬∫}\right)=\frac{4n_{1}n_{2}}{c^{2}\mu_{0}^{2}\sigma_{i}^{2}+\left(c\mu_{0}\sigma_{r}+n_{2}+n_{1}\right){}^{2}}.\label{eq:TransmittanceNormal}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Note that the transmittance is invariant with respect to the exchange of
 the media, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{1}\to n_{2}$
\end_inset

, but the reflectance is not.
 These results are shown in Fig.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:NormalIncidenceTM-1"

\end_inset

, for frequencies in the visible range, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in\left[380\text{nm},740\text{nm}\right]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Dimensional Analysis:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left[\vect K\right] & =\frac{C}{s}\\
\left[\vect E\right] & =\frac{V}{m}\\
\left[\sigma_{S}\right] & =\frac{\left[\vect K\right]}{\left[\vect E\right]}=\frac{mC}{Vs}=\frac{A}{V}\\
\left[\mu_{0}\right] & =\frac{N}{A^{2}}\\
\left[\mu_{0}c\sigma_{S}\right] & =\frac{Nm}{AVs}=\frac{C}{As}=1
\end{align*}

\end_inset

so, this means that the combination 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{0}c\sigma_{S}$
\end_inset

 is dimensionless.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Pictures/TM_NormalIncidence_GlasstoAir.pdf
	lyxscale 50
	scale 50

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Pictures/TM_NormalIncidence_AirtoGlass.pdf
	lyxscale 50
	scale 50

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:NormalIncidenceTM-1"

\end_inset

Normalized reflected, transmitted and absorbed radiation for a conducting
 sheet of graphene placed in an interface between a glass (
\begin_inset Formula $n=1.0$
\end_inset

) and air (
\begin_inset Formula $n=1.57$
\end_inset

).
 The situations corresponding to incidence from the glass and air side are
 considered.
 The temperature used was again 
\begin_inset Formula $T=300K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=-0.2\text{eV}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Total Reflection of Transverse Magnetic Waves
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before moving onto the next polarization, we need remark that all the calculatio
ns above were done assuming that transmission onto medium 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 is possible.
 Such is true for any angle if 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{2}\geq n_{1}$
\end_inset

, but otherwise, it only happens below the critical angle for total internal
 reflexion, i.e.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sin\theta_{\text{C}}=\frac{n_{2}}{n_{1}}\sin\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\right)=\frac{n_{2}}{n_{1}}.
\]

\end_inset

Above 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{\text{C}}$
\end_inset

, the wave in medium 2 is evanescent in the perpendicular direction, i.e.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\vect E_{t}\left(\overrightarrow{r},t\right) & =\vect E_{t,0}e^{i\left(k_{t,y}y+k_{t,z}z-\omega t+\phi_{t}\right)}e^{-\kappa x}\label{eq:ElectricFieldPlaneWave-1-1-1-1-2}\\
\vect B_{t}\left(\overrightarrow{r},t\right) & =\vect B_{t,0}e^{i\left(k_{t,y}y+k_{t,z}z-\omega t+\phi_{t}\right)}e^{-\kappa x}.\label{eq:MagneticFieldPlaneWave-1-1-1-1-2}
\end{align}

\end_inset

In this case, we have different relations between the two fields associated
 to the wave.
 In order to obtain these, we use again Faraday's Law ‚Äî 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\times\vect E_{t}\left(\overrightarrow{r},t\right)=-\nicefrac{\partial}{\partial t}\vect B_{t}\left(\overrightarrow{r},t\right)$
\end_inset

 ‚Äî yielding
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(i\kappa,k_{t,y},k_{t,z}\right)\times\vect E_{t}\left(\overrightarrow{r},t\right)=\abs{\begin{array}{ccc}
\hat{x} & \hat{y} & \hat{z}\\
i\kappa & k_{t,y} & k_{t,z}\\
E_{t,x} & E_{t,y} & E_{t,z}
\end{array}}=\omega\vect B_{t}\left(\overrightarrow{r},t\right),
\]

\end_inset

hence, we must have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{cases}
k_{t,y}E_{t,z}-k_{t,z}E_{t,y}=\omega B_{t,x}\\
k_{t,z}E_{t,x}-i\kappa E_{t,z}=\omega B_{t,y}\\
i\kappa E_{t,y}-k_{t,y}E_{t,x}=\omega B_{t,z}
\end{cases}.
\]

\end_inset

Since our magnetic field components along 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{y}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x}$
\end_inset

 are continuous, then 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{t,x}=B_{t,y}=0$
\end_inset

, for a TM polarized incident wave.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
[TO BE WRITTEN...]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Refraction of Transverse Electric (TE) Polarized Light
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this case, we have take the conventions defined in the right panel of
 Fig
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:BoundaryConditions-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Hence, the fields associated to each wave will be:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Incident Wave:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\vect E_{i}\left(\overrightarrow{r},t\right) & =-\abs{\vect E_{i}}e^{i\left(\overrightarrow{k}_{i}\cdot\overrightarrow{r}-\omega t\right)}\mathbf{\hat{z}}\label{eq:ElectricFieldPlaneWave-1-1-2}\\
\vect B_{i}\left(\overrightarrow{r},t\right) & =\abs{\vect B_{i}}e^{i\left(\overrightarrow{k}_{i}\cdot\overrightarrow{r}-\omega t\right)}\left[-\sin\theta_{i}\mathbf{\hat{x}}+\cos\theta_{i}\mathbf{\hat{y}}\right],\label{eq:MagneticFieldPlaneWave-1-1-2}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Reflected Wave:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\vect E_{r}\left(\overrightarrow{r},t\right) & =-\abs{\vect E_{r}}e^{i\left(\overrightarrow{k}_{r}\cdot\overrightarrow{r}-\omega t+\phi_{r}\right)}\mathbf{\hat{z}}\label{eq:ElectricFieldPlaneWave-1-1-1-2}\\
\vect B_{r}\left(\overrightarrow{r},t\right) & =-\abs{\vect B_{r}}e^{i\left(\overrightarrow{k}_{r}\cdot\overrightarrow{r}-\omega t+\phi_{r}\right)}\left[\sin\theta_{r}\mathbf{\hat{x}}+\cos\theta_{r}\mathbf{\hat{y}}\right],\label{eq:MagneticFieldPlaneWave-1-1-1-2}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Transmitted Wave:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\vect E_{t}\left(\overrightarrow{r},t\right) & =-\abs{\vect E_{t}}e^{i\left(\overrightarrow{k}_{t}\cdot\overrightarrow{r}-\omega t+\phi_{t}\right)}\mathbf{\hat{z}}\label{eq:ElectricFieldPlaneWave-1-1-1-1-1}\\
\vect B_{t}\left(\overrightarrow{r},t\right) & =\abs{\vect B_{t}}e^{i\left(\overrightarrow{k}_{t}\cdot\overrightarrow{r}-\omega t+\phi_{t}\right)}\left[-\sin\varphi\mathbf{\hat{x}}+\cos\varphi\mathbf{\hat{y}}\right],\label{eq:MagneticFieldPlaneWave-1-1-1-1-1}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Again, the frequency is the same and Snell's geometrical laws are valid.
 But note, however, that in this case the effect of discontinuity in the
 perpendicular component of the electric field is not important.
 That comes about from the fact that, by definition, one has 
\begin_inset Formula $\vect E\cdot\vect k=0$
\end_inset

.
 This means that we can write our version of the fields' boundary conditions
 for this polarization as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{cases}
\abs{\vect E_{i}}+e^{i\phi_{r}}\abs{\vect E_{r}}-e^{i\phi_{t}}\abs{\vect E_{t}} & =0\\
\sin\theta\abs{\vect B_{i}}+\sin\theta e^{i\phi_{r}}\abs{\vect B_{r}}-\sin\varphi e^{i\phi_{r}}\abs{\vect B_{r}} & =0\\
\cos\theta\abs{\vect B_{i}}-\cos\theta e^{i\phi_{r}}\abs{\vect B_{r}}-\cos\varphi e^{i\phi_{r}}\abs{\vect B_{t}}+\mu_{0}c\sigma_{S}e^{i\phi_{t}}\abs{\vect E_{t}} & =0
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

or, using the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\abs{\vect B}=v_{m}^{-1}\abs{\vect E}$
\end_inset

, we get to the following system:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{cases}
\abs{\vect E_{i}}+e^{i\phi_{r}}\abs{\vect E_{r}}-e^{i\phi_{t}}\abs{\vect E_{t}} & =0\\
\sin\theta\abs{\vect E_{i}}+\sin\theta e^{i\phi_{r}}\abs{\vect E_{r}}-\frac{n_{2}}{n_{1}}\sin\varphi e^{i\phi_{r}}\abs{\vect E_{r}} & =0\\
\cos\theta\abs{\vect E_{i}}-\cos\theta e^{i\phi_{r}}\abs{\vect E_{r}}-\left(\frac{n_{2}}{n_{1}}\cos\varphi e^{i\phi_{r}}+\frac{\mu_{0}c\sigma_{S}}{n_{1}}e^{i\phi_{t}}\right)\abs{\vect E_{t}} & =0
\end{cases}.
\]

\end_inset

As a matrix system, we have the following result:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
1 & e^{i\phi_{r}} & -e^{i\phi_{t}}\\
\sin\theta & \sin\theta e^{i\phi_{r}} & -\frac{n_{2}}{n_{1}}\sin\varphi e^{i\phi_{t}}\\
\cos\theta & -\cos\theta e^{i\phi_{r}} & -\left(\frac{n_{2}}{n_{1}}\cos\varphi+\frac{\mu_{0}c\sigma_{S}}{n_{1}}\right)e^{i\phi_{t}}
\end{array}\right)\cdot\left(\begin{array}{c}
\abs{\vect E_{i}}\\
\abs{\vect E_{r}}\\
\abs{\vect E_{t}}
\end{array}\right)=\left(\begin{array}{c}
0\\
0\\
0
\end{array}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which only yields a non-zero solution if the secular determinant is non-zero,
 i.e.
 if
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{e^{i\phi_{t}}\left(n_{1}\sin\theta-n_{2}\sin\varphi\right)\left(\xi n_{1}\left(-1+e^{i\phi_{r}}\right)e^{i\phi_{t}}-2n_{2}\cos\varphi e^{i\phi_{r}}\right)}{n_{1}^{2}}=0.
\]

\end_inset

This equation is automatically satisfied if Snell's Law of transmission
 is obeyed ‚Äî 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{1}\sin\theta=n_{2}\sin\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 So, in principle, we have transmission at all angles.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, we can we the two independent equations, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
\abs{\vect E_{i}}+e^{i\phi_{r}}\abs{\vect E_{r}}-e^{i\phi_{t}}\abs{\vect E_{t}} & =0\\
\cos\theta\abs{\vect E_{i}}-\cos\theta e^{i\phi_{r}}\abs{\vect E_{r}}-\left(\frac{n_{2}}{n_{1}}\cos\varphi e^{i\phi_{r}}+\frac{\mu_{0}c\sigma_{S}}{n_{1}}e^{i\phi_{t}}\right)\abs{\vect E_{t}} & =0
\end{cases},\label{eq:system}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

in order to find the conditions we are after, i.e.
 the transmittance, absorbance and reflectance.
 If we start by doing 
\begin_inset Formula $eq_{2}+eq_{1}\times\cos\theta$
\end_inset

, we get
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cos\theta\abs{\vect E_{i}}-\frac{1}{2}\left(\cos\theta+\frac{n_{2}}{n_{1}}\cos\varphi+\frac{\mu_{0}c\sigma_{S}}{n_{1}}\right)e^{i\phi_{t}}\abs{\vect E_{t}}=0
\]

\end_inset

thus yielding the following ratio of complex amplitudes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\abs{\vect E_{t}}e^{i\phi_{t}}}{\abs{\vect E_{i}}}=\frac{2n_{1}\cos\theta}{n_{1}\cos\theta+n_{2}\cos\varphi+\mu_{0}c\sigma_{S}}.\label{eq:TransmissionCoeffTE}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Replacing Eq.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:TransmissionCoeffTE"

\end_inset

 in the first line of the system in Eq.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:system"

\end_inset

 we get to the following result:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left(\frac{n_{2}\cos\varphi+\mu_{0}c\sigma_{S}-n_{1}\cos\theta}{n_{1}\cos\theta+n_{2}\cos\varphi+\mu_{0}c\sigma_{S}}\right)\abs{\vect E_{i}}+e^{i\phi_{r}}\abs{\vect E_{r}} & =0,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

yielding the following ratio
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\abs{\vect E_{r}}e^{i\phi_{r}}}{\abs{\vect E_{i}}}=\frac{n_{2}\cos\varphi-n_{1}\cos\theta+\mu_{0}c\sigma_{S}}{n_{1}\cos\theta+n_{2}\cos\varphi+\mu_{0}c\sigma_{S}}.\label{eq:TransmissionCoeffTE-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Once again, we can write the corresponding transmittance, reflectance and
 absorbance across the surface, as a function of the incidence angle, for
 a single layer with a complex conductivity, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{S}=\sigma_{r}+i\sigma_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 This yields the following results:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{T}_{\text{TE}}\left(\theta\right)=\frac{4n_{1}n_{2}\cos\theta\sqrt{1-\left(\frac{n_{1}}{n_{2}}\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\theta}}{c^{2}\mu_{0}^{2}\sigma_{i}^{2}+\left(c\mu_{0}\sigma_{r}+n_{2}\cos\theta+n_{1}\sqrt{1-\left(\frac{n_{1}}{n_{2}}\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\theta}\right){}^{2}}\label{eq:TE_Transmittance}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{R}_{\text{TE}}\left(\theta\right)=\frac{c^{2}\mu_{0}^{2}\sigma_{i}^{2}+\left(c\mu_{0}\sigma_{r}+n_{2}\cos\theta-n_{1}\sqrt{1-\left(\frac{n_{1}}{n_{2}}\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\theta}\right){}^{2}}{c^{2}\mu_{0}^{2}\sigma_{i}^{2}+\left(c\mu_{0}\sigma_{r}+n_{2}\cos\theta+n_{1}\sqrt{1-\left(\frac{n_{1}}{n_{2}}\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\theta}\right){}^{2}},\label{eq:TE_Reflectance}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which yield an absorbed energy per unit area in the graphene sheet of
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathcal{A}\left(\theta\right) & =4c\mu_{0}n_{1}\sigma_{r}\cos\theta\left(c^{2}\mu_{0}^{2}\left(\sigma_{i}^{2}+\sigma_{r}^{2}\right)+2n_{1}\cos\theta\left(c\mu_{0}\sigma_{r}+n_{2}\sqrt{1-\left(\frac{n_{1}}{n_{2}}\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\theta}\right)\right.\label{eq:TE_Absorption}\\
 & \qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\left.+2c\mu_{0}n_{2}\sigma_{r}\sqrt{1-\left(\frac{n_{1}}{n_{2}}\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\theta}+n_{1}^{2}\cos^{2}\theta+n_{2}^{2}\left(1-\left(\frac{n_{1}}{n_{2}}\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\theta\right)\right)^{-1}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

which obviously goes to zero in the limit when 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{r}\to0$
\end_inset

.
 In Fig.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:ObliqueIncidence"

\end_inset

, we depict 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{\text{TE}}\left(\theta\right)$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}_{\text{TE}}\left(\theta\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}_{\text{TE}}\left(\theta\right)$
\end_inset

 for a polarized wave with 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=500\text{nm}$
\end_inset

 incident on a glass-to-air and air-to-glass interface.
 Additionally, one can also check that they reduce to Eqs.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ReflectanceNormal"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:TransmittanceNormal"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 in the limit of normal incidence, as they should.
 At normal incidence, there is no distinction between a TE and a TM polarized
 wave.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Total Reflection of Transverse Electric Waves
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
[TO BE WRITTEN...]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Transmission of Non-polarized Light
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In some experiments, the incident light beam is not polarized.
 Instead, the polarization of the wave changes randomly in time, meaning
 that one will actually observe an average of the transmittances/reflectances
 for each of the polarizations analyzed above.
 This means that the effective values are as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathcal{R}_{\text{eff}}\left(\theta\right) & =\frac{1}{2}\left(\mathcal{R}_{\text{TM}}\left(\theta\right)+\mathcal{R}_{\text{TE}}\left(\theta\right)\right)=\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{1}{2}\left(1+\frac{c^{2}\mu_{0}^{2}\sigma_{i}^{2}+\left(c\mu_{0}\sigma_{r}+n_{2}\cos\theta-n_{1}\sqrt{1-\left(\frac{n_{1}}{n_{2}}\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\theta}\right){}^{2}}{c^{2}\mu_{0}^{2}\sigma_{i}^{2}+\left(c\mu_{0}\sigma_{r}+n_{2}\cos\theta+n_{1}\sqrt{1-\left(\frac{n_{1}}{n_{2}}\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\theta}\right){}^{2}}\right.\\
 & \qquad\left.-\frac{4n_{1}\cos\theta\sqrt{1-\left(\frac{n_{1}}{n_{2}}\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\theta}\left(c\mu_{0}\sigma_{r}+n_{2}\right)}{\left(1-\left(\frac{n_{1}}{n_{2}}\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\theta\right)\left(c^{2}\mu_{0}^{2}\sigma_{i}^{2}+\left(c\mu_{0}\sigma_{r}+n_{2}\right){}^{2}\right)+2n_{1}\cos\theta\sqrt{1-\left(\frac{n_{1}}{n_{2}}\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\theta}\left(c\mu_{0}\sigma_{r}+n_{2}\right)+n_{1}^{2}\cos^{2}\theta}\right)\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

and,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathcal{T}_{\text{eff}}\left(\theta\right) & =\frac{1}{2}\left(\mathcal{T}_{\text{TM}}\left(\theta\right)+\mathcal{T}_{\text{TE}}\left(\theta\right)\right)=\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{2n_{1}n_{2}\left(1-\left(\frac{n_{1}}{n_{2}}\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\theta\right)}{c^{2}\mu_{0}^{2}\sigma_{i}^{2}\left(1-\left(\frac{n_{1}}{n_{2}}\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\theta\right)+\left(\sqrt{1-\left(\frac{n_{1}}{n_{2}}\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\theta}\left(c\mu_{0}\sigma_{r}+n_{2}\right)+n_{1}\cos\theta\right){}^{2}}\\
 & \qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad+\frac{2n_{1}n_{2}\left(1-\left(\frac{n_{1}}{n_{2}}\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\theta\right)}{c^{2}\mu_{0}^{2}\sigma_{i}^{2}+\left(c\mu_{0}\sigma_{r}+n_{2}\cos\theta+n_{1}\sqrt{1-\left(\frac{n_{1}}{n_{2}}\right)^{2}\sin^{2}\theta}\right){}^{2}}.\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Plots of these two quantities are shown in Fig.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:ObliqueIncidence"

\end_inset

, as a function of the angle, for a glass-to-air and air-to-glass interfaces.
 These are then compared to the corresponding curves in the case of a bare
 interface, with no graphene deposited.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Pictures/Transmittance_Reflectance_Absorption_lambda500nm_ni1.00_nt1.57.pdf
	scale 50

\end_inset


\end_layout

