\begin_layout Section
Transfer-Matrix Method for Normal Incidence with Conducting Interfaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Till now, we considered only the transmission of electromagnetic waves across
 a single graphene layer placed on top of a glass surface.
 However, in many experiments, one is interested in the case where several
 layers of graphene, separated by dielectric media, scatter the incident
 wave.
 Treating this problem may be done easily by a transfer-matrix method.
 In a first approach, we describe the case when all the layers of graphene
 are parallel to each other and the incidence of EM radiation is normal
 to those surfaces.
 This situation does not distinguish between TM and TE polarizations and
 is depicted in Fig.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:TranferMatrix"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Pictures/TranferMatrix.pdf
	scale 28

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:TranferMatrix"

\end_inset

Left Panel: Scheme of the Transfer Matrix Method (TMM) for a layered structure
 of parallel graphene single-layers separated by dielectric media.
 Right Panel: Conventions used to define the transfer-matrix for the electric
 and magnetic fields at a single graphene interface.
 Only normal incidence is considered.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
General Theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Making use of the boundary conditions defined earlier for the electric and
 magnetic fields at an interface between two dielectric media of refractive
 indexes 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i+1}$
\end_inset

, with a graphene sheet deposed in between (as shown in the right panel
 of Fig.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:TranferMatrix"

\end_inset

), we obtain the following system of equations for the (complex) amplitudes
 at the boundary:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
E_{i,+}^{0}+E_{i,-}^{0}=E_{i+1,+}^{0}+E_{i+1,-}^{0}\\
B_{i,+}^{0}-B_{i,-}^{0}=B_{i+1,+}^{0}-B_{i+1,-}^{0}+\mu_{0}\sigma_{S}\left(E_{i,+}^{0}+E_{i,-}^{0}\right)
\end{cases}.\label{eq:System1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Additionally, we know that there are relations between the amplitudes of
 the electric and magnetic field components of a linearly polarized plane-wave
 propagating inside a dielectric medium.
 More precisely, with the conventions define in the right panel of Fig.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:TranferMatrix"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{cases}
B_{i,+}=\frac{n_{i}}{c}E_{i,+}\\
B_{i,-}=\frac{n_{i}}{c}E_{i,-}
\end{cases},
\]

\end_inset

which allows for the following generalization of the system in Eq.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:System1"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
E_{i,+}^{0}+E_{i,-}^{0}=E_{i+1,+}^{0}+E_{i+1,-}^{0}\\
E_{i,+}^{0}-E_{i,-}^{0}=\frac{n_{i+1}}{n_{i}}\left(E_{i+1,+}^{0}-E_{i+1,-}^{0}\right)+\frac{\mu_{0}c\sigma_{S}}{n_{i}}\left(E_{i,+}^{0}+E_{i,-}^{0}\right)\\
B_{i,+}^{0}+B_{i,-}^{0}=\frac{n_{i}}{n_{i+1}}\left(B_{i+1,+}^{0}+B_{i+1,-}^{0}\right)\\
B_{i,+}^{0}-B_{i,-}^{0}=B_{i+1,+}^{0}-B_{i+1,-}^{0}+\frac{\mu_{0}c\sigma_{S}}{n_{i}}\left(B_{i,+}^{0}+B_{i,-}^{0}\right)
\end{cases},\label{eq:System1-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

thus yielding, after some trivial algebra, the following system of equations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
E_{i,+}^{0}+E_{i,-}^{0}=E_{i+1,+}^{0}+E_{i+1,-}^{0}\\
\left(1-\frac{\mu_{0}c\sigma_{S}}{n_{i}}\right)E_{i,+}^{0}-\left(1+\frac{\mu_{0}c\sigma_{S}}{n_{i}}\right)E_{i,-}^{0}=\frac{n_{i+1}}{n_{i}}E_{i+1,+}^{0}-\frac{n_{i+1}}{n_{i}}E_{i+1,-}^{0}\\
B_{i,+}^{0}+B_{i,-}^{0}=\frac{n_{i}}{n_{i+1}}B_{i+1,+}^{0}+\frac{n_{i}}{n_{i+1}}B_{i+1,-}^{0}\\
\left(1-\frac{\mu_{0}c\sigma_{S}}{n_{i}}\right)B_{i,+}^{0}-\left(1+\frac{\mu_{0}c\sigma_{S}}{n_{i}}\right)B_{i,-}^{0}=B_{i+1,+}^{0}-B_{i+1,-}^{0}
\end{cases},\label{eq:System1-1-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

or, in matrix form,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\underset{\mathcal{M}_{1}}{\underbrace{\left(\begin{array}{cccc}
1 & 1 & 0 & 0\\
\left(1-\frac{\xi}{n_{i}}\right) & -\left(1+\frac{\xi}{n_{i}}\right) & 0 & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1 & 1\\
0 & 0 & \left(1-\frac{\xi}{n_{i}}\right) & -\left(1+\frac{\xi}{n_{i}}\right)
\end{array}\right)}}\cdot\left(\begin{array}{c}
E_{i,+}^{0}\\
E_{i,-}^{0}\\
B_{i,+}^{0}\\
B_{i,-}^{0}
\end{array}\right)=\underset{\mathcal{M}_{2}}{\underbrace{\left(\begin{array}{cccc}
1 & 1 & 0 & 0\\
\frac{n_{i+1}}{n_{i}} & -\frac{n_{i+1}}{n_{i}} & 0 & 0\\
0 & 0 & \frac{n_{i}}{n_{i+1}} & \frac{n_{i}}{n_{i+1}}\\
0 & 0 & 1 & -1
\end{array}\right)}}\cdot\left(\begin{array}{c}
E_{i+1,+}^{0}\\
E_{i+1,-}^{0}\\
B_{i+1,+}^{0}\\
B_{i+1,-}^{0}
\end{array}\right),\label{eq:MatrixForm1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi=\mu_{0}c\sigma_{S}$
\end_inset

.
 The matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}_{2}$
\end_inset

 can be explicitly inverted, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\left(\mathcal{M}_{2}\right)=4n_{i}/n_{i+1}$
\end_inset

.
 This yields,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{M}_{2}^{-1}=\frac{1}{2}\left(\begin{array}{cccc}
1 & \frac{n_{i+1}}{n_{i}} & 0 & 0\\
1 & -\frac{n_{i+1}}{n_{i}} & 0 & 0\\
0 & 0 & \frac{n_{i}}{n_{i+1}} & 1\\
0 & 0 & \frac{n_{i}}{n_{i+1}} & -1
\end{array}\right)
\]

\end_inset

and, multiplying both sides of Eq.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:MatrixForm1"

\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}_{2}^{-1}$
\end_inset

, we arrive at the following recursion relation for the complex field amplitudes
:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\begin{array}{c}
E_{i+1,+}^{0}\\
E_{i+1,-}^{0}\\
B_{i+1,+}^{0}\\
B_{i+1,-}^{0}
\end{array}\right)=\underset{\mathcal{T}_{G}\left(n_{i},,n_{i+1},\xi\right)}{\underbrace{\frac{1}{2}\left(\begin{array}{cccc}
1+\frac{n_{i}}{n_{i+1}}\left(1-\frac{\xi}{n_{i}}\right) & 1-\frac{n_{i}}{n_{i+1}}\left(1+\frac{\xi}{n_{i}}\right) & 0 & 0\\
1-\frac{n_{i}}{n_{i+1}}\left(1-\frac{\xi}{n_{i}}\right) & 1+\frac{n_{i}}{n_{i+1}}\left(1+\frac{\xi}{n_{i}}\right) & 0 & 0\\
0 & 0 & \frac{n_{i+1}}{n_{i}}+\left(\frac{\xi}{n_{i}}+1\right) & \frac{n_{i+1}}{n_{i}}-\left(1+\frac{\xi}{n_{i}}\right)\\
0 & 0 & \frac{n_{i+1}}{n_{i}}-\left(1+\frac{\xi}{n_{i}}\right) & \frac{n_{i+1}}{n_{i}}+\left(\frac{\xi}{n_{i}}+1\right)
\end{array}\right)}}\cdot\left(\begin{array}{c}
E_{i,+}^{0}\\
E_{i,-}^{0}\\
B_{i,+}^{0}\\
B_{i,-}^{0}
\end{array}\right).\label{eq:MatrixForm1-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{G}$
\end_inset

 is almost the transfer matrix for a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

chunk
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of material.
 However, this 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

chunk
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is not composed only by the infinitesimal width of graphene which established
 the boundary conditions.
 Before that there is a finite width 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{i}$
\end_inset

 of dielectric material which leads to the accumulation of a complex phase
 on the fields of the two counter-propagating EM plane-waves.
 The phase accumulated during this optical path length can be described
 by the following matrix:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{T}_{\phi}\left(n_{i},D_{i},\omega\right)=\left(\begin{array}{cccc}
e^{in_{i}D_{i}\omega c^{-1}} & 0 & 0 & 0\\
0 & e^{-in_{i}D_{i}\omega c^{-1}} & 0 & 0\\
0 & 0 & e^{in_{i}D_{i}\omega c^{-1}} & 0\\
0 & 0 & 0 & e^{-in_{i}D_{i}\omega c^{-1}}
\end{array}\right),
\]

\end_inset

which allows us to write the following transfer-matrix for the chunk 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{T}_{i}\left(n_{i},,n_{i+1},\xi,D_{i},\omega\right)=\mathcal{T}_{G}\left(n_{i},,n_{i+1},\xi\right)\cdot\mathcal{T}_{\phi}\left(n_{i},D_{i},\omega\right),
\]

\end_inset

thus yielding our final recursion relation:
\size tiny

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\begin{array}{c}
E_{i+1,+}^{0}\\
E_{i+1,-}^{0}\\
B_{i+1,+}^{0}\\
B_{i+1,-}^{0}
\end{array}\right)=\underset{\mathcal{T}_{i}\left(n_{i},,n_{i+1},\xi,D_{i},\omega\right)}{\underbrace{\frac{e^{\frac{i\omega D_{i}n_{i}}{c}}}{2}\left(\begin{array}{cccc}
\left(1+\left(1-\frac{\xi}{n_{i}}\right)\frac{n_{i}}{n_{i+1}}\right) & \left(1-(1+\frac{\xi}{n_{i}})\frac{n_{i}}{n_{i+1}}\right)e^{-\frac{2i\omega D_{i}n_{i}}{c}} & 0 & 0\\
\left(1-\left(1-\frac{\xi}{n_{i}}\right)\frac{n_{i}}{n_{i+1}}\right) & \left(1+\left(1+\frac{\xi}{n_{i}}\right)\frac{n_{i}}{n_{i+1}}\right)e^{-\frac{2i\omega D_{i}n_{i}}{c}} & 0 & 0\\
0 & 0 & \left(\frac{n_{i+1}}{n_{i}}+\left(1+\xi\right)\right) & \left(\frac{n_{i+1}}{n_{i}}-\left(1+\xi\right)\right)e^{-\frac{2i\omega D_{i}n_{i}}{c}}\\
0 & 0 & \left(\frac{n_{i+1}}{n_{i}}-\left(1+\xi\right)\right) & \left(\frac{n_{i+1}}{n_{i}}+\left(1+\xi\right)\right)e^{-\frac{2i\omega D_{i}n_{i}}{c}}
\end{array}\right)}}\cdot\left(\begin{array}{c}
E_{i,+}^{0}\\
E_{i,-}^{0}\\
B_{i,+}^{0}\\
B_{i,-}^{0}
\end{array}\right).
\]

\end_inset


\size default
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}\to\mathcal{T}_{G}$
\end_inset

 in the limit when 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{i}\to0$
\end_inset

, as it should.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we have a layered structure like the one in the left panel of Fig.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:TranferMatrix"

\end_inset

, we can relate the amplitudes of the fields in the two ends by successively
 applying 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{i}=\mathcal{T}\left(n_{i},,n_{i+1},\xi,D_{i},\omega\right)$
\end_inset

.
 More precisely, we have the following relation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\begin{array}{c}
E_{out,+}^{0}\\
0\\
B_{out,+}^{0}\\
0
\end{array}\right)=\underset{\mathcal{T}_{T}}{\underbrace{\mathcal{T}\left(n_{out},,n_{N-1},\xi,D_{N-1},\omega\right)\cdot\mathcal{T}_{N-2}\cdots\mathcal{T}_{1}\cdot\mathcal{T}_{G}\left(n_{in},n_{i+1},\xi\right)}}\cdot\left(\begin{array}{c}
E_{in,+}^{0}\\
E_{in,-}^{0}\\
B_{in,+}^{0}\\
B_{in,-}^{0}
\end{array}\right),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is the total number of Graphene layers deposed and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{T}$
\end_inset

 is the total transfer-matrix of the layered system.
 This is a 
\begin_inset Formula $4\times4$
\end_inset

 matrix, whose elements can be related to the (complex) transmission and
 reflection coefficients of the whole system.
 In general, we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\begin{array}{c}
E_{out,+}^{0}\\
0\\
B_{out,+}^{0}\\
0
\end{array}\right)=\left(\begin{array}{cccc}
t_{11}^{T} & t_{12}^{T} & t_{13}^{T} & t_{14}^{T}\\
t_{21}^{T} & t_{22}^{T} & t_{23}^{T} & t_{24}^{T}\\
t_{31}^{T} & t_{32}^{T} & t_{33}^{T} & t_{34}^{T}\\
t_{41}^{T} & t_{42}^{T} & t_{43}^{T} & t_{44}^{T}
\end{array}\right)\cdot\left(\begin{array}{c}
E_{in,+}^{0}\\
E_{in,-}^{0}\\
B_{in,+}^{0}\\
B_{in,-}^{0}
\end{array}\right),\label{eq:TransferMatrixEquation1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where we assumed, as a boundary condition at the last layer, that there
 is only a forward propagating wave.
 Despite its messy structure, we see that Eq.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:TransferMatrixEquation1"

\end_inset

, due to the block structure of the matrices involved, has the simpler structure
 of Eq.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:TransferMatrix2"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\begin{array}{c}
E_{out,+}^{0}\\
0\\
B_{out,+}^{0}\\
0
\end{array}\right)=\left(\begin{array}{cccc}
t_{11}^{T} & t_{12}^{T} & 0 & 0\\
t_{21}^{T} & t_{22}^{T} & 0 & 0\\
0 & 0 & t_{33}^{T} & t_{34}^{T}\\
0 & 0 & t_{43}^{T} & t_{44}^{T}
\end{array}\right)\cdot\left(\begin{array}{c}
E_{in,+}^{0}\\
E_{in,-}^{0}\\
B_{in,+}^{0}\\
B_{in,-}^{0}
\end{array}\right),\label{eq:TransferMatrix2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and hence the following useful relations emerge:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
E_{out,+}^{0}=t_{11}^{T}E_{in,+}^{0}+t_{12}^{T}E_{in,-}^{0}\\
t_{21}^{T}E_{in,+}^{0}+t_{22}^{T}E_{in,-}^{0}=0
\end{cases}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

These two equations imply that the reflection and transmission coefficients
 of the whole system are as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{cases}
r=\frac{E_{in,-}^{0}}{E_{in,+}^{0}}=-\frac{t_{21}^{T}}{t_{22}^{T}}\\
t=\frac{E_{out,+}^{0}}{E_{in,+}^{0}}=t_{11}^{T}-\frac{t_{12}^{T}t_{21}^{T}}{t_{22}^{T}}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

and, correspondingly, the reflectance, transmittance and absorbance of the
 whole system are
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{cases}
\mathcal{R}_{T}=\abs r^{2}=\frac{\abs{t_{21}^{T}}^{2}}{\abs{t_{22}^{T}}^{2}}\\
\mathcal{T}_{T}=\frac{n_{out}}{n_{in}}\abs t^{2}=\frac{n_{out}}{n_{in}}\abs{t_{11}^{T}-\frac{t_{12}^{T}t_{21}^{T}}{t_{22}^{T}}}^{2}\\
\mathcal{A}_{T}=1-\mathcal{R}_{T}-\mathcal{T}_{T}
\end{cases},
\]

\end_inset

which is all we wish to know about the system in question.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Numerical Implementation and Results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We built the entire transfer-matrix theory having 
\begin_inset Formula $4\times4$
\end_inset

 matrices as the main ingredients.
 However, we note that both 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{G}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{i}$
\end_inset

 are bock diagonal matrices with 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 blocks in either the electric and magnetic sectors.
 This fact indicates that, for normal incidence, it is redundant to care
 about both sectors and one can use only the electric field equations, i.e.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\begin{array}{c}
E_{i+1,+}^{0}\\
E_{i+1,-}^{0}
\end{array}\right)=\underset{\mathbb{T}_{i}\left(n_{i},n_{i+1},D_{i},\omega\right)}{\underbrace{\frac{1}{2}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\left(1+\left(1-\frac{\xi\left(\omega\right)}{n_{i}}\right)\frac{n_{i}}{n_{i+1}}\right)e^{\frac{i\omega D_{i}n_{i}}{c}} & \left(1-\left(1+\frac{\xi\left(\omega\right)}{n_{i}}\right)\frac{n_{i}}{n_{i+1}}\right)e^{-\frac{i\omega D_{i}n_{i}}{c}}\\
\left(1-\left(1-\frac{\xi\left(\omega\right)}{n_{i}}\right)\frac{n_{i}}{n_{i+1}}\right)e^{\frac{i\omega D_{i}n_{i}}{c}} & \left(1+\left(1+\frac{\xi\left(\omega\right)}{n_{i}}\right)\frac{n_{i}}{n_{i+1}}\right)e^{-\frac{i\omega D_{i}n_{i}}{c}}
\end{array}\right)}}\cdot\left(\begin{array}{c}
E_{i,+}^{0}\\
E_{i,-}^{0}
\end{array}\right),
\]

\end_inset

and consequently
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{T}_{T}=\underset{}{\mathbb{T}_{N-1}\left(n_{out},n_{N-1},D_{N-1},\omega\right)\cdot\mathbb{T}_{N-2}\left(n_{N-1},n_{N-2},D_{N-2},\omega\right)\cdots\mathbb{T}_{1}\left(n_{2},n_{1},D_{1},\omega\right)\cdot\mathbb{T}_{G}\left(n_{in},n_{1},\omega\right)},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbb{T}_{G}\left(n_{in},n_{1},\omega\right)=\frac{1}{2}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1+\frac{n_{i}}{n_{i+1}}\left(1-\frac{\xi}{n_{i}}\right) & 1-\frac{n_{i}}{n_{i+1}}\left(1+\frac{\xi}{n_{i}}\right)\\
1-\frac{n_{i}}{n_{i+1}}\left(1-\frac{\xi}{n_{i}}\right) & 1+\frac{n_{i}}{n_{i+1}}\left(1+\frac{\xi}{n_{i}}\right)
\end{array}\right)\label{eq:TG_Entrance}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and, again, 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi\left(\omega\right)=\mu_{0}c\left(\sigma_{r}\left(\omega\right)+i\sigma_{i}\left(\omega\right)\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Note that, in this formalism, the reflection coefficient of a single layer
 of graphene, placed in between two dielectrics 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{2}$
\end_inset

, is simply
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r=\frac{n_{2}-n_{1}-\frac{n_{2}}{n_{1}}\mu_{0}c\left[\sigma_{r}\left(\omega\right)+i\sigma_{i}\left(\omega\right)\right]}{n_{2}+n_{1}+\frac{n_{2}}{n_{1}}\mu_{0}c\left[\sigma_{r}\left(\omega\right)+i\sigma_{i}\left(\omega\right)\right]}
\]

\end_inset

and the transmission coefficients
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t=\frac{1}{2}\left\{ 1+\frac{n_{2}}{n_{1}}\left(1-\frac{\xi\left(\omega\right)}{n_{1}}\right)-\frac{\left[1-\frac{n_{2}}{n_{1}}\left(1-\frac{\xi\left(\omega\right)}{n_{1}}\right)\right]\left[1-\frac{n_{2}}{n_{1}}\left(1+\frac{\xi\left(\omega\right)}{n_{1}}\right)\right]}{1+\frac{n_{2}}{n_{1}}\left(1+\frac{\xi\left(\omega\right)}{n_{1}}\right)}\right\} ,
\]

\end_inset

which reduce to the coefficients calculated previously in the case of a
 single graphene sheet and an arbitrary angle of incidence.
 We can now implement the numerical calculation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{T}_{T}$
\end_inset

 for an arbitrary system.
 For this we only need to provide the following information to the computer:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Index of refraction of the incidence and transmission media ‚Äî 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{in}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{out}$
\end_inset

;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Complex conductivity of the graphene sheets (which is entirely determined
 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The widths (
\begin_inset Formula $D_{i}$
\end_inset

) and indexes of refraction (
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}$
\end_inset

) of all the dielectric separators.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Such situation is schematically represented in Fig.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset

, for different situations.
 Namely, we consider both the cases in which there is a fixed distance between
 the graphene sheets in the layered structure and also the
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Pictures/Reflectance_Lambda1500nmvsPolymerwidth_withscheme.pdf
	scale 25

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Pictures/Reflectance_Lambda1500nmvsPolymerwidth_withdisorder_withscheme.pdf
	scale 25

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Plots of the percentage of reflected intensity by the whole structure, as
 a function of the number of deposed graphene layers.
 In the upper panel, we represent this quantity for different (fixed) values
 for the distance between graphene planes, ranging from 
\begin_inset Formula $10$
\end_inset

nm to 
\begin_inset Formula $40$
\end_inset

nm.
 In the lower panel, we represent the same quantity but with a random realizatio
n of distances between planes, with a symmetric tolerance of 
\begin_inset Formula $10$
\end_inset

nm around the average 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{poly}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Transfer-Matrix Method for Oblique Incidence with Conducting Interfaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Simulation Results and Analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Field Reconstruction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Method
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Employing the afore constructed machinery, the system
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\begin{array}{c}
E_{out,+}\\
0
\end{array}\right)=\mathcal{T}_{T}\left(\begin{array}{c}
E_{in,+}\\
E_{in,-}
\end{array}\right)
\]

\end_inset

when normalized to the incident electric field becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\begin{array}{c}
t\\
0
\end{array}\right)=\mathcal{T}_{T}\left(\begin{array}{c}
1\\
r
\end{array}\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Knowing the 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 coefficient we must only successively apply matrix equilvalent to each
 layer to the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\begin{array}{c}
1\\
r
\end{array}\right)$
\end_inset

 to construct the field at each layer of the system.
 Notice that to achieve this we must build the system twice, once to discover
 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, and then again to construct the field given the initial conditions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename /home/rmp/Projects/Transfer_Matrix/Plots/Plot_Field/field_vs_d_20layer_Xig_wl1000.pdf

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
